<br>
For me, however there is the additional issue of Mythria's reputation. Im sure that is of concern to her as well... Consider the following:<br>
<br>
1] No one witnessed her do it, not even Aailin.<br>
<br>
2] The log contains nothing other than her taunting in character. This is after Aailin admitted (reluctantly, I might add; he only did so after ImperialSon mentioned it) that they were also taunting in character.<br>
<br>
Her taunts would prove nothing in a court of law. She *may* have been taunting after training them OR she may have been responding in kind. One can only speculate. It is *not* damning evidence.<br>
<br>
3] Tthere are people who have pointed out that it would have been difficult (if not impossible) for her to train those mobs, even had she wanted to.<br>
<br>
So we have Aailin admitting he did not witness her do it; we have her taunts in character, which could merely be retaliation for previous taunting (ie, she admits nothing in her taunts); and there has been doubt cast on her ability to have been the trainer in the first place.<br>
<br>
Like I said, I understand that many people are only concerned with Viv's response, and frankly I find that very disappointing, considering this thread has taken real shots at someones reputation based on what could well be circumstantial evidence.<br>
<br>
Robin: I understand the reasoning behind your last post, but it does ***NOT*** change the situation I mentioned above. Yes, Aailin did log the incident, and yes, he did approach it in a well-documented and correct manner. He should be appluaded for doing so. But does that make it correct to torpedo someone based on circumstantial evidence?<br>
<br>
No.<br>
<br>
As Ive said all along, there are two elements here: Viv's response and Mythria's guilt. I find dismissing Mythria's possible innocence to be grossly neglectful and offensive. I do think Aailin (who has steadfastly judged her as guilty) and everyone who has jumped on that bandwagon, especially in light of the circumstantial evidence presented, owes her an apology.<br>
<br>
If Aailin receives flack for that aspect of all this, I feel it is justified.<br>
