 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A> at: 9/5/02 2:39:53 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uindigoaven.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Indigo Aven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/5/02 2:19:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=186>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sister of Myth...dishonored and griefers</span><hr size=1> I hesitated to post on this this subject, but some things said here really disturb me.  Before I start, I should say that the opinions expressed here are ooc and I hope they won't have an effect on my guild.<br>
<br>
Never, ever, under any circumstances should people defend training.  Examples I have seen of defending training:<br>
<br>
1)  No one died:  Ah, I see, so the rule is, if you train and no one dies, then things are all cool.  Wow, I never knew that, I wish I would have got this addendum to the Play nice policies. <br>
<br>
2) If you raid a town, expect to be trained:  I love this one, because it is totally true.  Using the word &quot;expect&quot; changes everything.  I know I can expect to be trained because there are jackasses out there who would do this kind of thing.  Does this mean I have to like it?  Does this mean I have to accept it?  Does this mean its ok?<br>
<br>
3) You were taunting the people: Just for the sake of argument, let's assume this is true.  In fact, let's go as far as to say that all of them were cussing people out, beating on the poor Tier'dal kid in the alley, and stealing platnium from the town's banker.  If all these things were true, does that make training ok?  I'd like to think that there is a more mature way to handle things.  If not, use /petition.<br>
<br>
Ok, now that I have dealt with that, let me say that I understand why people defending the sisters.  Some people may of thought it was harsh to open this to the public.  Yes, this may be so, but I think all the poster was looking for was an apology or hell, maybe something as simple as the fact that she was going to look into it and take some sort of action.  What he got back wouldn't have satisfied me if I were in his shoes, so I probably would have done something.  Would I go to the boards?  Maybe not, but then again, I will not fault him for this action.<br>
<br>
Also, I do not think he was rash in accusing Mythria of the training.  I am looking at this situation from a totally indifferent point of view.  First, he says he saw her run past.  Ok, we can chalk that up to hearsay.  Next comes the logs.  Mythria knew of the event, becuase she said something about him running from sisters.  Does this make her the trainer?  Not at all, just puts her there at the time of the event.  Next, he sends a tell to the guildleader and Vivienne first response is she knows of her daughter's activities?  Hmm, if I were in his shoe, I would be more suspect, though there is still no proof.  This is the kicker for me, though again, this may be out of context, so it's not proof, but if I were him, I'd probably be convinced:<br>
<br>
&quot;nobody did . so she used her brain to get revenge upon those who normally couldn't&quot;<br>
<br>
No straight out confession of training, though I believe I would assume the &quot;she&quot; is Mythria and the &quot;revenge&quot; was training, but these are both assumptions.  Given these things, I would have come to the same conclusion.  <br>
<br>
Hell, even after the event in question, I am still puzzled by one of Mizzery's responses.  In this thread ( <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showMessage?topicID=1337.topic">pub94.ezboard.com/ffirion...1337.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> ) Mizzery writes a paragraph about &quot;Are you positive Mythria trained you?&quot;  Aren't you an officer, don't you know what happened?  The fact that you would question if he knows instead of flat out saying, &quot;I have talked with my sister, and she claims she had no part of it&quot; bothers me.  I see three scenarios for you.  1) You haven't talked to Mythria, in which case you don't have all the facts, so making him look like the guilty one isn't exactly the right thing to do.  2) You talked to her, and she claims she did it, in which case you shouldn't put up these questions and are doing so just out of spite.  3)  You talked to her and she claims she didn't do it, in which case, you should have stated that you talked to her, and you don't believe him.<br>
<br>
The posters only flaw here in this was implicating the whole guild.  The actions of a few people in a guild should not reflect the guild as a whole.  <br>
<br>
I am sorry if I have offended anyone by defending the poster, but I believe that alot of things are being said against him are completely unfair, and I cannot in good conscious keep my mouth closed.<br>
