 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/urobingoodfellow.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Robin Goodfellow</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 770<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/5/02 3:18:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=193>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sister of Myth...dishonored and griefers</span><hr size=1> Isharra, Caillou, Aailin, et. al.:<br>
<br>
The sad fact is that most guild leaders behave like this.  They usually believe their guildmates over strangers their guildmates have wronged.  They are often as blind about the faults of their guildmates as parents are blind about the faults of their children.  They also know that there is really nothing that someone bringing a grievance to them can do to them.  There are some stock excuses guildleaders will use to absolve themselves of any culpability: &quot;I wasn't there&quot;, &quot;I know her/him and s/he wouldn't do that kind of thing&quot;, &quot;Why should I believe you, a stranger, over her/him, my friend?&quot;, &quot;S/he's denying s/he had anything to do with it, and I stand by her/him.&quot;  Taking things to a guild's leader is useless.<br>
<br>
This situation would not have happened if the guild's leader had simply said &quot;I'm sorry that happened to you.  I'll look into the matter and take appropriate action.&quot;  Those words, especially &quot;sorry&quot;, do not appear to be in most guild leaders' vocabularies, and this particular guild leader is not an exception.<br>
<br>
There is a lesson to be learned here for all guild leaders.  Apologies go a lot further towards assuaging bad feelings than defensiveness and they cost nothing to give.  Apologizing for a guildmate's bad behavior does not make your guild look bad.  If someone believes your guildmate has wronged them, arguing with them about it will make them think the entire guild is bad, while apologizing will lead them to believe it was genuinely an accident.  Unfortunately, I think this lesson will get lost in all the shouting (and because I am the one articulating it).<br>
<br>
There is also a lesson to be learned here for the rest of us.  Everyone says that you should take grievances to the guild's leadership, but my own experience confirms Aailin's story.  Guild leadership is more interested in saving face than resolving disputes.  If you want a dispute resolve, taking it to a guild's leadership will not be fruitful.  Taking it here will not be fruitful, either, because a significant number of people here believe that anyone with a complaint is &quot;just a whiner&quot; and your reputation suffers, too, not because it should, but because popular opinion is irrational.<br>
<br>
That leaves only two courses of action:<br>
1) do nothing, or<br>
2) /petition and /report quietly, put the person on /ignore if need be<br>
...and then go about your business. <p>"These discourses of heterosexuality oppress us in the sense that they prevent us from speaking unless we speak in their terms."<BR>
-Monique Wittig, "The Straight Mind"<BR>
andersonrob@earthlink.net<BR>
http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/index.html<BR>
AIM: RWAnderson<BR>
ICQ: 43988595<BR>
EverQuest: Lasgalen Lothir of Lux Aeternam, Firiona Vie server<BR>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uisharramoonsong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Isharra Moonsong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 533<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/5/02 3:29:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=194>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.earthlink.net/~brennec/_uimages/Isharra.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sister of Myth...dishonored and griefers</span><hr size=1> Robin:<br>
<br>
That's where the difference between a good guild and a bad guild lies: good guilds care about their reputations and take steps to preserve them even in the face of injust opposition. They do so through courtesy and respect, not temper tantrums or defensiveness. <br>
<br>
Good guild leaders listen to all complaints courteously and then take steps to resolve the complaint in a way that benefits all people involved, members and nonmembers. Bad guild leaders say, &quot;I don't care what you or anyone thinks. I must defend my member tooth and nail.&quot; <br>
<br>
I've led guilds, and showing courtesy and respect towards others goes a long way in resolving potentially ugly disputes.<br>
<br>
Mizzery took some pretty good steps toward that goal; Vivienne did not. <br>
<br>
So please, do go to guildleaders first, because if it is a good guild, the leader will listen to you and do his own investigation before dismissing your issue. And there are lots of good guilds out there; problem is, they usually have the type of people who don't need reporting. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
