<br>
For what it's worth: I don't hold Myth responsible for anything. If she *did* train Aailin, it was her GL responsibility to tell her she was wrong. If she didn't train Aailin, it is her guild leader's responsibility to investigate the matter and let Aailin know he has the wrong person. She didn't so much as even deny Myth did it when Aailin approached her, and in fact, if you read the logs, Viv seems to applaud that Myth may have trained Aailin. <br>
<br>
THAT'S the problem. Right off the bat, Aailin was thwarted from using the appropriate channels, and had to come here. If Myth has a bad reputation because of it, it's because Vivienne did not take the proper steps to remedy the situation when she was approached, NOT because Aailin came here with his grievance. <br>
<br>
I honestly don't think anyone is holding Myth responsible. I can't even remember how to spell the girl's name---that's how little I noticed her role. The crime here was committed by Vivienne, not Myth, and Vivienne has yet to state definitively that training, for ANY reason, is prohibited in her guild.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugnosisgnome.showPublicProfile?language=EN>GnosisGnome</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 122<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/5/02 4:06:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=19.topic&index=198>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sister of Myth...dishonored and griefers</span><hr size=1> Lasgalen,<br>
<br>
Let me open this with the disclaimer that I don't wish to be perceived as saying something nice about SoM or their guildleader. I know very little about the guild firsthand, and what little I know is negative. About their leadership I know nothing.<br>
<br>
I have to disagree with the spirit of what you have said, however, when you wrote<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The sad fact is that most guild leaders behave like this. They usually believe their guildmates over strangers their guildmates have wronged. They are often as blind about the faults of their guildmates as parents are blind about the faults of their children. They also know that there is really nothing that someone bringing a grievance to them can do to them. There are some stock excuses guildleaders will use to absolve themselves of any culpability: &quot;I wasn't there&quot;, &quot;I know her/him and s/he wouldn't do that kind of thing&quot;, &quot;Why should I believe you, a stranger, over her/him, my friend?&quot;, &quot;S/he's denying s/he had anything to do with it, and I stand by her/him.&quot; Taking things to a guild's leader is useless.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
In the truth of what you say, you may be right. Most guild leaders do tend to give the benefit of the doubt to their guildies. I think, however, that this is a good thing for the most part. One should listen to complaints and should confront one's guldies with accusations against them, but if it degenerates into a &quot;he said/she said,&quot; in the end one must trust in one's own guildie. If you cannot trust your guildies, then the problem runs deep into recruitment, not in any particular incident.<br>
<br>
When I say I disagree with the spirit of what you have said, I mean this: Just because there is a good chance that your complaints will not be taken seriously does not mean you should not take the incident to the guildleader (or some other officer, if the guildleader is unavailable). Sure, there are some guilds out there with some pretty piss-poor officers, but you should always give them the opportunity first. If a guildleader abdicates her responsibility or, even worse, encourages nastiness (such as appears to be the situation here), then it becomes appropriate to bring the issue before the larger community.<br>
<br>
You seem to be suggesting that because some guilds (maybe even most as you suggest) have poor leadership, the victim should not bother with informing the guild. I can speak for at least ONE guild on this server to say that such complaints are always taken seriously, even when the outcome is not to the petitioner's liking. I would hate to think that some of my guildies are out there violating the EULA or the PNP and no one is telling us for fear that they may be ignored.<br>
<br>
If I were a betting gnome, I'd be willing to bet that Ledenyetz Troupe isn't the only guild for which your statement that &quot;Taking things to a guild's leader is useless&quot; is untrue. I'm also willing to bet that there are officers in other guilds out there WANT to hear of misconduct by their members so that they can deal with it before that bad apple spoils the whole barrel.<br>
<br>
Yours,<br>
Gnosis Bunglefoot<br>
